# WordPress Coding Standards (WPCS)

Theme code should align with the official **[WordPress Coding Standards](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/)** and linked handbooks:

- **[PHP](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/php/)** — spacing, naming, Yoda where required, `elseif`, no short tags, etc.
- **[JavaScript](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/javascript/)** — admin / Customizer bundles in `src/admin/`.
- **[HTML](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/html/)** — valid markup, semantics, attributes.
- **[CSS](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/css/)** — together with theme rules in `scss-css.mdc` / `admin-src-scss.mdc`.
- **[Accessibility](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/accessibility/)** — aim for **WCAG 2.x AA** patterns (labels, focus, contrast, ARIA when needed).

## WordPress security & i18n habits

- **Escape output:** `esc_html()`, `esc_attr()`, `esc_url()`, `wp_kses_post()`, etc., as appropriate.
- **Sanitize input** in settings and `sanitize_callback` on Customizer settings.
- **Internationalization:** use `__()`, `_e()`, `esc_html__()`, … with the theme **text domain** (e.g. `'onepress'`) for user-facing strings.

## Scope

- **Third-party / vendored** libraries are not rewritten to WPCS; glue code and theme-owned files should still follow WPCS where it applies.

## Tooling (optional)

- Local checks may use **PHPCS** with the **WordPress** ruleset (`wp-coding-standards/wpcs`) when installed; match project config if present.
